Don't forget to stop by to get repairs done on broken devices. We will have staff available from 9am to 4pm at 2220 N. 59th Street (North Central Office) this week.

Fee Chart:
iPads and Chromebooks
○ Physical damage $25
○ Missing charger $25
○ Device missing or stolen $50
MacBook Air
○ LCD/Screen damage $50 (or 7 hours of community service)
○ Keyboard damage $40 (or 5 hours of community service)
○ Damaged/missing charger $25 (or 4 hours of community service)
○ Liquid spill, lost, stolen $150"

... and yes we are still trying to figure out how ⬇️⬇️ happened.

* What does my schedule look like?

post_text:
Sports announcement: The Kansas City, Kansas School Board votes 5 to 2 to suspend all involvement in KSHSAA fall sports. This will include: football, volleyball, cross country, girls tennis, boys soccer. The vote also suspends marching band and spirit squad.

The vote only involves fall sports and will allow the board time to re-evaluate covid cases before making a decision about winter sports.

In addition, the board has agreed to re-evaluate cross country and tennis based on any recommendations given in the future from the WYCO health department.

An executive session has been called for tonight to discuss the roles of many of the districts coaches.

post_text:
The KCKPS votes to make revisions to the 2020-2021 school year.

The updated changes to the calendar will make revisions in previously scheduled holiday breaks, family advocacy days, and move the start of the school year for students to Tuesday, September 8th to better align with other districts in the area. The changes will allow for the end of the school year to only be pushed back by one day for both students and teachers.

The first nine weeks will remain remote learning ONLY.

In addition, the updated calendar moves the start date for all returning teachers back to August 17th and eliminates Wednesday professional development half days for the entire school year. The state mandates how many hours each student is required to be in class (Kindergarten through 11th grade: 1116 hours, 12th grade: 1086 hours). These changes allow for the district to meet those mandated hours.

To view entire calendar:https://kckps.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/2020-21-District-Calendar-Updated-08-03-2020-Plan-A-1.pdf

post_text: Despite the Kansas State Board of Education voting against the passing of Governor Laura Kelly’s Executive Order, the KCKPS Board voted last night to follow Governor Kelly’s recommendation and will start school on September 9th.
shared_text:
KMBC.COM
Kansas Board of Education nixes Gov. Kelly's order; local districts to decide opening dates

KMBC 9
July 22 at 12:04 PM ·

The Kansas State Board of Education has scuttled Gov. Laura Kelly’s executive order that would push the start date of schools until after Labor Day.

With their 5-5 vote, the board of education’s decision means local school districts will determine when they start classes in the fall. The order did not pass since there was no simple majority from the board.

The vote impacts more than 519,000 elementary, middle and high school students, teachers, staff and administrators across the Sunflower State.

post_text:
Update: Governor will sign two executive orders. One, will not require a board approval and means that all staff, students, etc in K-12 buildings will be required to wear a mask. Everyone will have to have their temperatures taken daily. Exceptions to mask: medical or mental issues, those that are deaf or when speaking to someone that is deaf.

Second executive order will have to be voted on. This order will delay the start of school until Sept. 9th. This includes not only school but also sports will be delayed until after Labor Day.

KCKPS response to the governor's announcement:

We appreciate today’s announcement by Governor Laura Kelly to delay the reopening of schools until after Labor Day. The Governor’s decision will allow KCKPS additional time to discuss and evaluate our proposed options for reopening school. We understand there will be additional questions related to what the delay will mean for our school district, we plan to provide those details in the coming days. The health and safety of our students, staff and their families will always remain a priority as we continue to review reopening options.

post_text: AMBER ALERT IN KCK: Please be on the lookout for Olivia. Anyone with information should call 911 or 913-596-3000.
shared_text:
KMBC.COM
Kansas issues Amber Alert for missing KCK 3-year-old girl

KMBC 9
July 10 at 11:40 AM ·

🚨KEEP FLOODING YOUR FEEDS🚨 An Amber Alert has been issued for a missing 3-year-old girl in Kansas City, Kansas.

The Kansas City, Kansas Police Department said Olivia Ann Jansen was last seen early this Friday at her residence in the 4400 block of Gibbs Road in Kansas City, Kansas. Police said she was last seen wearing pink pajamas.

Police said at 6:30 a.m., Jansen's father woke up and discovered that she was not in the residence and the back door of the location was standing open. Police said due to her age and location they believe she was taken from the location.

Police said there is no known suspect at this time.

Anyone with information on her location is asked to call 911 or 913-596-3000.

post_text:
In response to #COVID19, families with children who received free or reduced meals this last school year will receive up to $291 per child to purchase food.

How to receive pandemic EBT:
👉 Families with children who participate in programs including SNAP food assistance, child care assistance, or TANF cash assistance: The one-time benefit will be automatically loaded onto your EBT card in the next few weeks
👉 If your family doesn't participate in SNAP, child care assistance, or TANF, but you do have kids participating in free/reduced lunch, you will be mailed a pre-loaded card in the next few weeks.
